A computer-implemented method for issuing a governmental permit or clearance as a digital credential, comprising:
  receiving, by a server, an application request from a user device comprising personal data and payment credentials;
  locking, by a smart contract executed on a blockchain, a payment amount associated with the application request in an escrow state;
  processing, by a machine learning risk engine, the personal data to generate a risk score indicative of fraud probability;
  dynamically determining a validity period for the digital credential based on the risk score;
  generating a Verifiable Credential (VC) comprising a cryptographic signature of a government authority and the determined validity period, wherein the VC is generated only if the risk score is below a predetermined threshold;
  triggering, by the smart contract, a release of the locked payment amount to a government treasury address upon receipt of the cryptographic signature; and
  transmitting the generated Verifiable Credential to a digital wallet application associated with the user device.

A system for issuing digital governmental permits, comprising:
  a processor and a memory storing instructions that, when executed, cause the system to:
  interface with a user digital wallet to receive an application payload;
  interface with a blockchain network to instantiate a payment escrow smart contract;
  execute a machine learning model to assess application risk;
  generate a W3C-compliant Verifiable Credential if the application risk is within acceptable parameters;
  sign the Verifiable Credential with a private key associated with a Decentralized Identifier (DID) of the government authority; and
  update the payment escrow smart contract to finalize the transaction upon successful credential generation.

The method of claim 1, further comprising:
  receiving a verification request from a third-party verifier node;
  generating a proof of possession by the digital wallet;
  transmitting the proof to the third-party verifier node; and
  validating the proof against the blockchain without requiring the third-party verifier node to access the central government database.
